<p>
    In each of the following scenarios,
    we consider the distribution of a quantity along an axis.

    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Suppose that the function
          <m>c(x) = 200 + 100 e^{-0.1x}</m> models the density of traffic on a straight road,
          measured in cars per mile,
          where <m>x</m> is number of miles east of a major interchange,
          and consider the definite integral <m>\int_0^2 (200 + 100 e^{-0.1x}) \, dx</m>.

          <ol marker="i.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Complete the following blanks to determine and justify the units on the product <m>c(x) \cdot \Delta x</m>.
              </p>
              <p sectionWideCheckWork>
                Since the units on <m>c(x)</m> are <choiceInput inline name="c1">
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice>cars</choice>
                  <choice>miles</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">cars per mile</choice>
                  <choice>miles per car</choice>
                </choiceInput> and the units on <m>x</m> (and therefore on <m>\Delta x</m>) are <choiceInput inline name="c2">
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice>cars</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">miles</choice>
                  <choice>cars per mile</choice>
                  <choice>miles per car</choice>
                </choiceInput>, it follows that the units on <m>c(x) \cdot \Delta x</m> are <choiceInput inline name="c3">
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">cars</choice>
                  <choice>miles</choice>
                  <choice>cars per mile</choice>
                  <choice>miles per car</choice>
                </choiceInput>
              </p>
              <p>
                <answer><award><when>($c1=cars per mile) and ($c2=miles) and ($c3=cars)</when></award></answer>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                State the units on the definite integral <m>\int_0^2 c(x) \, dx</m> and its Riemann sum approximation 
                <me>
                  \int_0^2 c(x) \, dx \approx \sum_{i=1}^n c(x_i) \Delta x?
                </me>
              </p>
              <p>
                The units on <m>\int_0^2 c(x) \, dx \approx \sum_{i=1}^n c(x_i) \Delta x</m> are
                <answer><choiceInput>
                  <choice credit="1">cars</choice>
                  <choice>miles</choice>
                  <choice>cars per mile</choice>
                  <choice>miles per car</choice></choiceInput></answer>
              </p>              
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate the definite integral
                <m>\int_0^2 c(x) \, dx = \int_0^2 \left(200 + 100 e^{-0.1x}\right) \, dx</m> and complete the following sentence to state and explain the meaning of its value.
              </p>
              <p>
                We find that <m>\int_0^2 c(x) \, dx = </m> <mathInput name = "math_ans"></mathInput>, which is the
                <choiceInput name="c4">
                  <choice>number of cars per mile, on average, between mile <m>0</m> and mile <m>2</m></choice>
                  <choice>total number of cars between mile <m>0</m> and mile <m>2</m></choice>
                  <choice>total number of miles traveled by all the cars</choice>
                </choiceInput>                
              </p>
              <p>
                <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when> 
                $math_ans = 1400 - 1000e^(-0.2) and $c4.selectedIndices=2
              </when></award></answer>
              </p>  
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          On a 6 foot long shelf filled with books,
          the function <m>B</m> models the distribution of the weight of the books,
          in pounds per inch,
          where <m>x</m> is the number of inches from the left end of the bookshelf.
          Let <m>B(x)</m> be given by the rule <m>B(x) = 0.5 + \frac{1}{(x+1)^2}</m>.

          <ol marker="i.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Complete the following blanks to determine and justify the units on the product <m>B(x) \cdot \Delta x</m>.
              </p>
              <p sectionWideCheckWork>
                Since the units on <m>B(x)</m> are <choiceInput inline name="b1">
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice>inches</choice>
                  <choice>books</choice>
                  <choice>inches per book</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">books per inch</choice>
                </choiceInput> and the units on <m>x</m> (and therefore on <m>\Delta x</m>) are <choiceInput inline name="b2">
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">inches</choice>
                  <choice>books</choice>
                  <choice>inches per book</choice>
                  <choice>books per inch</choice>
                </choiceInput>, it follows that the units on <m>c(x) \cdot \Delta x</m> are <choiceInput inline name="b3">
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice>inches</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">books</choice>
                  <choice>inches per book</choice>
                  <choice>books per inch</choice>
                </choiceInput>
              </p>
              <p>
                <answer><award><when>($b1=books per inch) and ($b2=inches) and ($b3=books)</when></award></answer>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                State the units on the definite integral <m>\int_{12}^{36} B(x) \, dx</m> and its Riemann sum approximation 
                <me>
                  \int_{12}^{36} B(x) \, dx \approx \sum_{i=1}^n B(x_i) \Delta x
                </me>
              </p>
              <p>
                The units on <m>\int_{12}^{36} B(x) \, dx \approx \sum_{i=1}^n B(x_i) \Delta x</m> are
                <answer><choiceInput>
                  <choice>inches</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">books</choice>
                  <choice>books per inch</choice>
                  <choice>inches per book</choice></choiceInput></answer>
              </p>  
            </li>

            <li>           
              <p>
                Evaluate the definite integral
                <m>\int_{12}^{36} B(x) \, dx = \int_{12}^{36} \left(0.5 + \frac{1}{(x+1)^2}\right) \, dx</m> and complete the following sentence to state and explain the meaning of its value.
              </p>
              <p>
                We find that <m>\int_{12}^{36} B(x) \, dx = </m> <mathInput name = "math_ans2"></mathInput>, which is the 
                <choiceInput name="b4">
                  <choice>number of books per inch, on average, between inch <m>12</m> and inch <m>36</m></choice>
                  <choice>total number of books on the shelf</choice>
                  <choice>total number of inches that are covered by books</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">total number of books on the shelf between inch <m>12</m> and inch <m>36</m></choice>
                </choiceInput>                
              </p>
              <p>
                <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when> 
                $math_ans2 = 12-(37^(-1)-13^(-1)) and $b4.selectedIndices=4
              </when></award></answer>
              </p>               
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>